The reissued Model 52B is equipped with several elements consistent with the original, including a steel buttplate, a checkered stock with an ebony forend tip and steel grip cap, a high polish blue finish and a 5-round detachable magazine. The rifle features a Micro Motion trigger with easily accessible screws for over travel and pull weight adjustment. This Model 52B is in Fine condition, with only a few minor marks on the metal surfaces and several marks on the stock. This is a very nice .22 rifle, which will accept a wide range of scopes, making it great for target shooting or varmint control.

title: For Trade:  P-26 M91 Dragoon Mosin Nagant
postcontent:
Up for trade ONLY, my P-26 M91 Dragoon. I don't want to get rid of this one, but considering my collection revolves more around Civil Guard related items, especially M24s, I figured I'd put this up to see if there's any interest. If not, I certainly have no problem keeping this one in the safe. ;)

This one was a pre-bubba rescue. The previous owner was going to refinish the metal and wood, make a pretty "shooter" out of it. With the help of a very good friend, this one escaped that fate.

This one I would say is in overall fair condition. There's not much finish left on the metal surfaces, has a nice patina though. The stock is in good, solid condition, no cracks - a Finn-made stock, rear portion was part of a one-piece Russian M91 stock that saw use in Austria-Hungary, you can see the plugs under the escutcheons and on the bottom of the stock. Has solid M91 Dragoon bands and what I've been told is a modified Japanese Type 38 cleaning rod - has the same age/patina as the rifle, I'd imagine its been with the rifle for quite some time. It does have a Finnish makers mark stamped onto the wood. The bore is poor condition, visible rifling, but looks very neglected - may clean up though, I've done a couple soaks with CLP and the rifling shows more definition with each cleaning - considering the rarity, I'll leave it to the next owner to try and clean it more if they so choose. I have not shot this rifle. The rifle originally came with a canvas M1 Garand sling on the hangers, I've replaced it with an SA marked Soviet M91/30 sling, but if a trade is done the next owner is more than welcome to the Garand sling that was on it.

These are very rare, this one is one of only a handful of known existing examples. Only 1490 M91 Dragoon barrels were relined along with the P series M91 Infantry rifle barrels. This would be a fine addition to any Finn/mosin collection, even with its issues. Not that it matters much other than for shipping purposes, but the receiver is a 1902 Tula.

Here are a couple pages with a bit more info on these:

http://www.mosinnagant.net/finland/M91inFinland.asp
http://7.62x54r.net/MosinID/MosinMPseries.htm

If you need more pictures, please email me.

Alright, now what I'm looking for in possible trade - in order of preference:

NSD marked M24
Updated M28 (M28 with M28/30 upgrades)
Civilian M28
Possibly other Civil Guard related rifles - though NOT the more commonly seen variants of M24s, M91s, M28s, etc - If I let this go it will ONLY be for something of near equivalent rarity/value/etc.

This will not be a for sale listing, no price will be added. This is for trade ONLY. 

If you're interested and have something you'd be willing to offer from the list above, please email me. I can provide my cell number from there if you'd prefer to discuss over the phone rather than email. 

Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale:  IWI Tavor FDE 5.56 NATO NIB
postcontent: The dynamics of the battlefield are forever changing. With the increasing threat of terrorism in our streets to the evolving situations of combat applications, a new paradigm in firearms was required. In 1982, with the foresight of what the modern battlefield was becoming, IWI in a decade long collaboration with the Israel Defense Forces (IDF) Research & Development teams, developed the new standard issue weapon for the IDF. The TAVOR® was born. Mr. Zalman Shebs, known as the “father of the TAVOR,” spearheaded the team to develop a weapon system that was capable of moving from open field conflicts to close-quarter engagements and from daylight to nighttime capabilities – seamlessly on a single mission. In the late 1990’s through the early 2000’s, the TAVOR underwent unprecedented testing unlike any weapons system anywhere. The TAVOR began trials with IDF units testing for ergonomics. The TAVOR then entered the IDF NCO Infantry School for extensive field tests and finally, in 2002, the TAVOR was given to an army company in the Givati Brigade for real-world testing and use. By September, 2003, the IDF had chosen the TAVOR rifle as the standard issue for their infantry troops. Today the TAVOR rifles are in service with IDF Infantry troops and the IDF Special Forces in Israel along with many military and law enforcement agencies around the world.
